trans-unit.source: The ATAN2 function returns the arctangent, in radians, of the quotient of the two arguments.

seg-source.mrk: The ATAN2 function returns the arctangent, in radians, of the quotient of the two arguments.

target.mrk: The ATAN2 function returns the arctangent, in radians, of the quotient of the two arguments.

trans-unit.source: Upon successful completion, the function returns the arc tangent of y/x in the range -pi to pi radians, where y is the first argument and x is the second argument. The specified numbers must be DOUBLE PRECISION numbers.

seg-source.mrk: Upon successful completion, the function returns the arc tangent of y/x in the range -pi to pi radians, where y is the first argument and x is the second argument.
The specified numbers must be <xref href="rrefsqljdoubleprecision.dita#rrefsqljdoubleprecision">DOUBLE PRECISION</xref> numbers.

target.mrk: Upon successful completion, the function returns the arc tangent of y/x in the range -pi to pi radians, where y is the first argument and x is the second argument.
The specified numbers must be <xref href="rrefsqljdoubleprecision.dita#rrefsqljdoubleprecision">DOUBLE PRECISION</xref> numbers.

trans-unit.source: If either argument is NULL, the result of the function is NULL.

seg-source.mrk: If either argument is NULL, the result of the function is NULL.

target.mrk: If either argument is NULL, the result of the function is NULL.

trans-unit.source: If the first argument is zero and the second argument is positive, the result of the function is zero.

seg-source.mrk: If the first argument is zero and the second argument is positive, the result of the function is zero.

target.mrk: If the first argument is zero and the second argument is positive, the result of the function is zero.

trans-unit.source: If the first argument is zero and the second argument is negative, the result of the function is the double value closest to pi.

target.mrk: If the first argument is zero and the second argument is negative, the result of the function is the double value closest to pi.
